World & Core Mechanics

    The simulator needs a 2D NxM grid.

    The simulation must be turn-based.

    Each cell can hold a maximum of one organism at a time.

    Actions are ordered first by the highest initiative, and then by age for ties.

    Collisions are resolved by comparing strength, where the stronger organism wins. If strengths are equal, the attacker wins.

Core Classes & Architecture

    A World class is required to manage gameplay, hold the organisms, and handle turns via methods like makeTurn() and drawWorld().

    An abstract Organism base class must be created with fields for strength, initiative, position, and a reference to the world. It requires action(), collision(), and draw() methods.

    An Animal abstract subclass must be implemented to handle base random movement and multiplication upon colliding with another animal of the same species.

    A Plant abstract subclass must be created with a default initiative of 0. It must implement a probability to "sow" or spread to a neighboring free cell during its action.

Specific Organisms

    The Human Player: There must be exactly one human on the map, controlled by the arrow keys, with a base strength of 5 and initiative of 4.

    Special Ability: You must implement exactly one chosen special ability for the Human (Immortality, Magical potion, Antelope's speed, Alzur's shield, or Purification). This ability must last for 5 turns and have a 5-turn cooldown period.

    Animals: You need to implement specific subclasses for the Wolf, Sheep, Fox, Turtle, and Antelope. (Note: The Cyber-sheep is only mandatory if you are building the project in Python ).

    Plants: You need to implement specific subclasses for Grass, Sow thistle, Guarana, Belladonna, and Sosnowsky's hogweed.

UI and Initialization

    The simulation must begin with several instances of each organism type already spawned in the world.

    You must include a text box or console line to display event messages, such as fight results or plant consumption.

    Your first name, last name, and index number must be displayed somewhere in the user interface.

Language-Specific Milestone Features

    If building in C++: The project requires a console UI using ASCII symbols. To achieve full marks (5 points), you must implement save and load functionality to and from a file.

    If building in Java or Python: The project requires a GUI library, like Swing for Java. For 4 points, you need to allow users to add new organisms of any kind by clicking on a free map cell. For 5 points, you must abstract the world to support both standard grid and hexagonal grid layouts.


